# [[Unlimited Risk Definition and Example]]

> ## Excerpt
> Unlimited [[Risk|risk]] is when the risk of an investment is unlimited, although steps can be taken to help control actual losses.

---

[[Unlimited Risk Definition and Example]]
## What Is Unlimited [[Risk]]?

Unlimited [[Risk|risk]] refers to a situation where there is potential for unlimited losses on a trade or in a particular investment. Any time an asset's price can move indefinitely against a trader's position means they are facing unlimited risk. A [[short trade]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/short.asp) is an example of a strategy with unlimited risk.

### Key Takeaways

-   Unlimited [[Risk|risk]] has to do with trades or investments that can theoretically face unlimited losses.
-   Selling naked calls is an example of unlimited [[Risk|risk]].
-   While [[Risk|risk]] can be unlimited, generally speaking the investor can mitigate much of the risks.

While unlimited [[Risk|risk]] trades theoretically have unlimited risk, the trader doesn't actually have to assume unlimited risk. They can take steps to limit actual losses, such as [[hedging]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/h/[[Hedge|hedge]].asp) or setting [[stop loss orders]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/stop-lossorder.asp).

## Understanding Unlimited [[Risk]]

Unlimited [[Risk|risk]] is the opposite of [[limited risk]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/l/limitedrisk.asp). With unlimited risk, there is the potential to lose more than your initial investment, which is possible in [[Short Selling|short selling]], in trading [[Futures|futures]] contracts, or when [[writing naked options]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/n/naked-writer.asp).1

[[Risk]] itself refers to the probability that an investment [[Will|will]] have an [[actual return]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/actualreturn.asp) different from the [[Return|return]] that the investor expected. Risk ranges from losing some of one's investment to potentially losing the entirety of the original investment. With unlimited risk, it is possible (but not necessarily likely) to lose many times the amount of the original investment.

[[Risk]] varies from investment to investment, and one form of assessing risk can be calculated by using the [[standard deviation]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/standarddeviation.asp) of the [[Historical Returns|historical returns]] or average returns of a specific investment, with a higher [[Standard Deviation|standard deviation]] indicating a higher degree of risk.

Though the process may be intimidating, investors make high-[[Risk|risk]] investments regularly and for various logical reasons. The main justification is that, in [[finance]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/[[Finance|finance]].asp), theoretically, the greater the risk to an investor the greater the potential [[Return|return]]. The higher potential return compensates for the additional risk taken on by the investor.2

## Controlling [[Risk]] and Unlimited Risk

Unlimited [[Risk|risk]] may make it sound like making certain trades or certain investments aren't worthwhile. For example, since [[Short Selling|short selling]] has theoretically unlimited risk, certain traders may avoid it. While risk is theoretically unlimited, it isn't actually unlimited unless a trader (and their broker) allow that to happen.

A trader could enter a short trade in a [[Stock|stock]] at $5 and decide that they [[Will|will]] [[close]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/closeposition.asp) the short trade if the price moves up to $5.50. In this case, their actual [[Risk|risk]] is $0.50 per share and is not unlimited. The price could [[gap]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/g/gap.asp) above their stop loss price of $5.50, say to $6 or $7. This would certainly increase the loss, but the loss is still capped to $1 or $2 where the stop loss would trigger in these cases.

The same concept applies to [[futures contracts]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/[[Futures|futures]].asp) or writing naked options. When losing money, a trade can be closed. The price at which a trader closes the position determines their actual loss.

It is possible that the loss could be more than they initially invested in the trade, or even more than they have in their [[Trading Account|trading account]]. When this occurs, it is called a [[margin call]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/margincall.asp) and the broker [[Will|will]] ask the trader to deposit funds in order for them to maintain their position (if still open) or bring their account balance up to zero. If the trading account drops below zero due to a trading loss, this means the trader has a [[Debt|debt]] to the broker.

## Examples of Unlimited [[Risk]] When Writing Naked Options

Assume that a trader is interested in writing [[naked calls]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/n/nakedcall.asp) on Apple Inc. ([AAPL](https://www.investopedia.com/markets/[[Quote|quote]]?tvwidgetsymbol=aapl)). The writer [[Will|will]] receive the [[option premium]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/o/option-[[Premium|premium]].asp), which is their maximum profit. If the price of AAPL is below the [[strike price]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/strikeprice.asp) at expiry, the option writer gets to keep the premium as their profit on the trade.

If the price of AAPL rises above the strike price, the option writer faces theoretically unlimited [[Risk|risk]], since there is no cap on how high the price could rise. The writer has agreed to sell [[Shares|shares]] of AAPL at the strike price to the buyer of the call option. This means the option writer [[Will|will]] need to buy shares of AAPL in order to sell them to the buyer at the strike price, regardless of the market price of AAPL at that time.

Assume one call option is written with a strike price of $250, which [[Will|will]] expire in three months. The current price of AAPL [[Stock|stock]] is $240.50. The option is sold for $6.35, which means the writer receives $635 ($6.35 x 100 [[Shares|shares]] for one contract).

If the price of AAPL [[Shares|shares]] stay below $250, the writer keeps the $635 or a portion of it if they close the position early.

If AAPL rises above $250 then they face unlimited losses, but they can still control how much they lose, to an extent. For example, if AAPL rises to $255 before expiry, they may decide to cut their losses and exit their options trade.

If the price of AAPL is trading at $255 at expiry, the writer still hasn't lost money. This is because they can buy AAPL for $5 above the strike price ($255) in order to sell it at the strike price ($250). They lose $5 there, but made $6.35 on the option, so they still pocket $1.35 per share, less fees.

If the price of AAPL is trading at $270 at expiry, the naked option writer has lost money. They need to pay $20 more than the strike price ($270 â€“ $250) in order to sell the [[Shares|shares]] at the strike price ($250). They lose $20 here, but made $6.35 on the option sale, so they end up losing $13.65 per contract. Their theoretical loss was unlimited, but the actual loss was $13.65 per contract. This could potentially be reduced through the use of stop losses, exiting early when losing, buying the shares for a [[covered call]](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/coveredcall.asp) strategy, or hedging.
